the first element, as in   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McWaters","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the personal name   Walter  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wahler","meanings":["German:","from the personal name <i>Wol(d)er</i>, Low German form of   Walter  .","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wahl, Wahle, or Wahlen."]},{"name":"McWalter","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b> ‘son of   Walter  ’."]},{"name":"Walters","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Walther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Wolfgang, Otto, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Bernd, Bernhard.","German, Dutch, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Lauter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Erwin, Kurt, Sigismund, Wolf.","German: topographic name and habitational name, from a common stream name meaning ‘clear’, from Middle High German <i>hlutra</i>, or from any of the places called Lauter or Lauta (Saxony). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and some other European countries.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lavtar</b> or its Croatized and rare Slovenian variant <b>Lautar</b>: from a dialect variant of the personal name <i>Valter</i> (see   Walter  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Walter was born in 1500, in Roxwell, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Walter, was 25 and his mother, Thomesine Heveningham, was 22. He married Isabell Denton in 1530, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died on 14 April 1536, in his hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1500–14 Apr 1536":"1500–14. aprill 1536","1500–1536":"1500–1536","1490–1588":"1490–1588","1534–1581":"1534–1581","1538–Male":"1538–Surnud","1542–Female":"1542–Surnud","1545–Female":"1545–Surnud","1475–1530":"1475–1530","1478–1513":"1478–1513","14 Apr 1536":"14. aprill 1536","1 Jun 1513":"1. juuni 1513","1581":"1581","Jan 1534":"jaanuar 1534","1490":"1490","abt 1530":"1530","1536":"1536","1513":"1513","1545":"1545","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1478":"1478","1588":"1588","1499":"1499","1542":"1542","1530":"1530","1475":"1475","1538":"1538","Roxwell, Essex, England":"Roxwell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Roxwell, Chelmsford, Essex, England":"Roxwell, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Billingshurst, Sussex, England":"Billingshurst, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1500–14 Apr 1536":"1500–14. huhtikuuta 1536","1500–1536":"1500–1536","1490–1588":"1490–1588","1534–1581":"1534–1581","1538–Male":"1538–Kuollut","1542–Female":"1542–Kuollut","1545–Female":"1545–Kuollut","1475–153